name: Jugoslavijo
comments: Also known as "Od Vardara pa do Triglava". A popular song in the former Yugoslavia from the mid 1970s on and kind of an inofficial national anthem of the former Yugoslavian state (the official one was "Hej slaveni"). In addition to the folk melody from Macedonia, the text celebrates the unity and history of Yugoslavia uniting the people from Vardar (most southern river of ex-Yugoslavia) to Triglav (most northern and highest mountain, now Slovenia) and from Djerdap (the Serbian border region to Romania) to the Adriatic sea in the West.

Besides its French name "Frère Jacques" is known by a variety of names: in Afrikaans as "Vader Jakob"; in Croatian as "Bratec Martin";  in Czech as "Bratře Kubo"; in Danish as "Mester Jakob"; in Dutch as "Broeder Jacob" (in Flanders) or "Vader Jacob" (in the Netherlands); in English as "Brother John", in Finnish as "Jaakko kulta"; in German as "Meister Jakob" or "Bruder Jakob"; in Hebrew as "אחינו הנהג" (romanized as "Achinu HaNehag"); in Hungarian as "János bácsi"; in Italian as "Fra' Martino"; in Polish as "Panie Janie"; in Slovenian as "Mojster Jaka" and in Spanish as either "Fray Santiago" or "Martinillo".

comments: The title meaning "Risen from ruins", this was the national anthem of the former German Democratic Republic ('East Germany') in 1949 and remained so until the so called German reunification in 1990. Becher had been commissioned by GDR's Politbüro of the Central Committee to write the lyrics for a to be anthem. Interstingly, he measured the metre to fit to "Gott erhalte Franz den Kaiser", which is the basis for both Austria's and entire Germany's anthems. Becher asked the composers Ottmar Gerster and Hanns Eisler to set music to his lyrics. After two presentations, the Politburo decided in favor of Eisler's compostition. This was then premiered on Nov. 7th, 1949 (the 32nd anniversary of the October Revolution) at the Admiralspalast, which at the time served as East Berlin's opera house.
